{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:21:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:21:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17185"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17185"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.7,0.09,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109485"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17185"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91852"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5590"},{"type":"tags","id":"5601"},{"type":"tags","id":"5604"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40330"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109485"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the Pre-admission Clinic for assessment before elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy. He has a history of obstructive sleep apnoea, obesity with a body mass index of 35 kg/m\u00b2, type 2 diabetes mellitus and ankylosing spondylitis. His medications include metformin, sulfasalazine and paracetamol as required. He is a non-smoker and works as an accountant. On examination, he appears well with pulse rate 72/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO\u2082 96% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. His Mallampati score is class II, thyromental distance is 6.5 cm, and he has severely limited neck extension and lateral rotation due to his ankylosing spondylitis. He can open his mouth to four cm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is most predictive of difficult intubation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyromental distance of 6.5 cm","Mouth opening of four cm","Limited neck mobility","Body mass index of 35 kg/m\u00b2","Mallampati class II"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPre-operative airway assessment is crucial for identifying patients at risk of difficult intubation. Multiple factors contribute to airway difficulty, and their combination provides better predictive value than any single factor alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimited neck mobility\u003C/strong\u003E is the most predictive single factor for difficult intubation in this patient. Adequate neck extension is crucial for optimal alignment of the oral, pharyngeal and laryngeal axes during direct laryngoscopy. When neck mobility is severely restricted, as in this patient with ankylosing spondylitis, achieving this alignment becomes significantly more challenging. Studies have shown that limited neck mobility has a high positive predictive value for difficult intubation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMallampati class II\u003C/strong\u003E has moderate predictive value when used as a standalone test. However, Mallampati classes III and IV are more strongly associated with difficult intubation. Class II alone is not considered a strong predictor of difficulty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyromental distance of 6.5 cm\u003C/strong\u003E is within the normal range. A thyromental distance of less than six cm suggests that intubation using conventional, direct laryngoscopy may be very difficult or impossible. This patient\u0027s measurement of 6.5 cm is adequate and not predictive of difficult intubation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMouth opening of four cm\u003C/strong\u003E is adequate for intubation. Reduced mouth opening (less than three cm inter-incisor distance) can make laryngoscopy difficult, but this patient\u0027s mouth opening exceeds this threshold and is not a concern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBody mass index of 35 kg/m\u00b2\u003C/strong\u003E indicates class II obesity. While obesity is associated with difficult bag-mask ventilation and can complicate airway management, BMI alone has poor predictive value for difficult intubation. Other factors such as neck circumference and fat distribution may be more relevant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple airway assessment factors should be evaluated in combination for better prediction of difficult intubation.","Patients with ankylosing spondylitis require careful airway planning due to restricted cervical spine mobility."],"references":["Crawley, SM et al. Predicting the difficult airway. British Journal of Anaesthesia Education, Volume 15, Issue 5, 253 - 25, 2015.","Harjai M, Alam S, Bhaskar P. Clinical Relevance of Mallampati Grading in Predicting Difficult Intubation in the Era of Various New Clinical Predictors. Cureus. 2021 Jul 14;13(7):e16396. doi: 10.7759/cureus.16396. PMID: 34408949; PMCID: PMC8362876.","Nickson C. Airway Assessment [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2019 [cited 2025 Jul 6]. Available from: https://litfl.com/airway-assessment/","Bradley P, Chapman G, Crooke B, Greenland K; Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists. Airway assessment. Melbourne: ANZCA; 2016. (Airway resource series; 1). Available from: https://www.anzca.edu.au/getContentAsset/c50e48ef-cbb8-4093-b2af-eff208c07a48/80feb437-d24d-46b8-a858-4a2a28b9b970/PU-Airway-Assessment-20160916v1.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17185"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91852"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T19:59:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T20:00:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109485"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},